            "      <meta content=\"Delivery &amp; Pickup Options - 996 reviews of Milk &amp; Cream Cereal Bar &quot;This is a new ice cream spot that just opened up in chinatown. Their concept revolves around cereal. They have 3 main items to choose from, cereal bowl, ice cream cone, or ice cream milkshake. Each item comes with your choice of cereal added in. And you can choose which kind of topping, and drizzle you want. They also have some specials you can choose from as well. I decided on getting the ice cream swirl with Frosted Flakes as my cereal and cookie crunchies as the topping on a matcha konery cone. It was pretty yummy, I liked the texture of the ice cream and you can taste and see the cereal embedded into it. My friend got the milkshake and she enjoyed it as well. The reason why I have to deduct a star is because of the amount of time we had to wait for our order. We didn't really have to wait to put in our order but we waited like 15-20 minutes after paying to get our order and there was only like 2 ppl ahead of us. I'm not sure if this was because they are new and still working some things out but it was too long of a wait. I think they only have 2 machines they use to blend the ice cream and cereal and 2 guys making the orders. I wonder how long the wait would've been if there were to have been more ppl ahead.&quot;\" data-rh=\"true\" name=\"description\"/>\n",

There&apos;s a bright neon sign up front that people love to take photos in front of. Unlike many other social media dessert playgrounds that lack any substance, the ice cream at Milk &amp; Cream is quite tasty, and you have a long list of choices when it comes to what cereal you want blended into it. Most of the classics are on the menu, and the machine they have to blend the ingredients together does a great job of distributing just the right amount of cereal throughout the ice cream, so each bite is equally satisfying.\\n\\nWith every subsequent visit I am finding the ice cream here more and more overly sweet, and it doesn&apos;t help that every single cereal choice they have is a very sweet one, almost without exception. It would be nice to have more neutral options like Crispx, plain Cheerios, or even Kix, since the ice cream itself is already very sweet. I realize though they&apos;re not catering to palates like mine, as much as I crave sweets, but to people who would gladly make &quot;there&apos;s no such thing as too sweet&quot; the mantra of their life.             "                          4 check-ins\n",
            "                         </span>\n",
            "                        </span>\n",
            "                       </div>\n",
            "                      </div>\n",
            "                      <div class=\"lemon--div__373c0__1mboc margin-b2__373c0__abANL border-color--default__373c0__3-ifU\">\n",
            "                       <p class=\"lemon--p__373c0__3Qnnj text__373c0__2Kxyz comment__373c0__3EKjH text-color--normal__373c0__3xep9 text-align--left__373c0__2XGa-\">\n",
            "                        <span class=\"lemon--span__373c0__3997G raw__373c0__3rcx7\" lang=\"en\">\n",
            "                         Ice cream blended with any cereal of your choice is the premise of a business pulled straight out of a sugar fiend's wildest dreams, and here it is come to life. They've really blown up after many media appearances as well as partnerships with Spot Dessert Bar, with influencers like @foodbabyny, and even with Nickelodeon. Their marketing tactics are slick but they actually have a quality product to show for it. My sweet tooth has brought me here on a number of occasions over the years and I've tried everything from their chocolate s'mores galore to their milkshakes.\n",
            "                         <br/>\n",
            "                         <br/>\n",
            "                         I think what really worked for Milk &amp; Cream is that they were one of the earlier purveyors of dessert made for the Instagram age. Each ice cream swirl is made picture perfectly, replete with cute toppings like teddy grahams and caramel drizzles. There's a bright neon sign up front that people love to take photos in front of. Unlike many other social media dessert playgrounds that lack any substance, the ice cream at Milk &amp; Cream is quite tasty, and you have a long list of choices when it comes to what cereal you want blended into it. Most of the classics are on the menu, and the machine they have to blend the ingredients together does a great job of distributing just the right amount of cereal throughout the ice cream, so each bite is equally satisfying.\n",
            "                         <br/>\n",
            "                         <br/>\n",
            "                         With every subsequent visit I am finding the ice cream here more and more overly sweet, and it doesn't help that every single cereal choice they have is a very sweet one, almost without exception. It would be nice to have more neutral options like Crispx, plain Cheerios, or even Kix, since the ice cream itself is already very sweet. I realize though they're not catering to palates like mine, as much as I crave sweets, but to people who would gladly make \"there's no such thing as too sweet\" the mantra of their life. If this is you, this is your place.\n",
            "                        </span>\n",
            "                       </p>\n",
            "                      </div>\n",

They&amp;#39;ve really blown up after many media appearances as well as partnerships with Spot Dessert Bar, with influencers like @foodbabyny, and even with Nickelodeon. Their marketing tactics are slick but they actually have a quality product to show for it. My sweet tooth has brought me here on a number of occasions over the years and I&amp;#39;ve tried everything from their chocolate s&amp;#39;mores galore to their milkshakes.<br&gt;<br&gt;I think what really worked for Milk &amp;amp; Cream is that they were one of the earlier purveyors of dessert made for the Instagram age. Each ice cream swirl is made picture perfectly, replete with cute toppings like teddy grahams and caramel drizzles. There&amp;#39;s a bright neon sign up front that people love to take photos in front of. Unlike many other social media dessert playgrounds that lack any substance, the ice cream at Milk &amp;amp; Cream is quite tasty, and you have a long list of choices when it comes to what cereal you want blended into it. Most of the classics are on the menu, and the machine they have to blend the ingredients together does a great job of distributing just the right amount of cereal throughout the ice cream, so each bite is equally satisfying.<br&gt;<br&gt;With every subsequent visit I am finding the ice cream here more and more overly sweet, and it doesn&amp;#39;t help that every single cereal choice they have is a very sweet one, almost without exception. It would be nice to have more neutral options like Crispx, plain Cheerios, or even Kix, since the ice cream itself is already very sweet. I realize though they&amp;#39;re not catering to palates like mine, as much as I crave sweets, but to people who would gladly make &amp;#34;there&amp;#39;s no such thing as too sweet&amp;#34; the mantra of their life. Their concept revolves around cereal. They have 3 main items to choose from, cereal bowl, ice cream cone, or ice cream milkshake. Each item comes with your choice of cereal added in. I decided on getting the ice cream swirl with Frosted Flakes as my cereal and cookie crunchies as the topping on a matcha konery cone. It was pretty yummy, I liked the texture of the ice cream and you can taste and see the cereal embedded into it. My friend got the milkshake and she enjoyed it as well. The reason why I have to deduct a star is because of the amount of time we had to wait for our order. We didn&#x27;t really have to wait to put in our order but we waited like 15-20 minutes after paying to get our order and there was only like 2 ppl ahead of us. I&#x27;m not sure if this was because they are new and still working some things out but it was too long of a wait. I think they only have 2 machines they use to blend the ice cream and cereal and 2 guys making the orders. They&#x27;ve really blown up after many media appearances as well as partnerships with Spot Dessert Bar, with influencers like @foodbabyny, and even with Nickelodeon. Their marketing tactics are slick but they actually have a quality product to show for it. My sweet tooth has brought me here on a number of occasions over the years and I&#x27;ve tried everything from their chocolate s&#x27;mores galore to their milkshakes.\\n\\nI think what really worked for Milk &amp; Cream is that they were one of the earlier purveyors of dessert made for the Instagram age. Each ice cream swirl is made picture perfectly, replete with cute toppings like teddy grahams and caramel drizzles. There&#x27;s a bright neon sign up front that people love to take photos in front of. Unlike many other social media dessert playgrounds that lack any substance, the ice cream at Milk &amp; Cream is quite tasty, and you have a long list of choices when it comes to what cereal you want blended into it. Most of the classics are on the menu, and the machine they have to blend the ingredients together does a great job of distributing just the right amount of cereal throughout the ice cream, so each bite is equally satisfying.\\n\\nWith every subsequent visit I am finding the ice cream here more and more overly sweet, and it doesn&#x27;t help that every single cereal choice they have is a very sweet one, almost without exception. It would be nice to have more neutral options like Crispx, plain Cheerios, or even Kix, since the ice cream itself is already very sweet. I realize though they&#x27;re not catering to palates like mine, as much as I crave sweets, but to people who would gladly make \\&quot;there&#x27;s no such thing as too sweet\\&quot; the mantra of their life.
